    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1947-05-21T03:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1947-05-21T03:00:00-05:00" n="508"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d508">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">861.4054/5–2147: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in the Soviet Union</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Durbrow</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">restricted</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Moscow</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1947-05-21T11:00:00+03:00"
                            >May 21, 1947—11 a. m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>1843. Applicant for immigration visa informed Embassy recently that Assistant
                    Chief of <gloss target="#t_OVIR1">OVIR</gloss> (exit visa issuing office) told
                    her that cases of “private citizens desiring to depart from Soviet Union are not
                    being considered as present time.” This additional evidence that wives of
                    American citizens (<gloss target="#t_Embtels1">Embtel</gloss> 1203 April 5) will
                    not be allowed to depart. Also indicates high level decision on whole question
                    of exit visas has been or is in process of being made.<note n="1"
                        xml:id="d508fn1">The Chargé further reported in telegram 2058 from Moscow on
                        June 7, noon, not printed, that Soviet authorities were even preventing the
                        departure of Americans whose citizenship had been verified and who were mot
                        dual nationals. Notes had been written on 8 cases, involving 10 individuals,
                        but the Chargé believed that, because of the seriousness of the arbitrary
                        action, Ambassador Smith should take up the matter at a high level upon his
                        return to the Embassy.</note>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Durbrow</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
